, the tribunal may make a decision without a hearing.</p>\n\n<h2>Solve the dispute without a hearing</h2>\n\n<p>The Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service (<abbr title=\"Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service\">Acas</abbr>) may contact you when a claim is made. </p>\n\n<p>They&rsquo;ll offer you ways of solving the problem without a hearing.</p>\n\n<p>You can also call them for advice.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong><abbr title=\"Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service\">Acas</abbr></strong><br />\n08457 474 747</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Compromise agreements</h2>\n\n<p>You could also sign a compromise agreement. </p>\n\n<p>This offers the employee compensation, who in return drops their claim.</p>\n\n<p>The employee must get legal advice before they sign a compromise agreement. You&rsquo;ll usually have to pay all the legal fees.</p>\n\n<h2>Get help or legal advice</h2>\n\n<p>You may want to get <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.lawsociety.org.uk/find-a-solicitor/\" title=\"legal advice\">legal advice</a> if a claim is made against you.</p>\n\n<p>For general guidance on how the process works, call the employment tribunal enquiry line. They <strong>can&rsquo;t</strong> give legal advice.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Employment tribunal enquiry line</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Telephone:</strong> 0845 795 9775<br />\n<strong>Minicom:</strong> 0845 757 3722</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If you&rsquo;re in Northern Ireland</h2>\n\n<p>Your case will be dealt with by the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.employmenttribunalsni.co.uk/\" title=\"Office of Industrial Tribunals and the Fair Employment Tribunal.\">Office of Industrial Tribunals and the Fair Employment Tribunal.</a></p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/being-taken-to-employment-tribunal-by-employee/before-the-hearing","slug":"before-the-hearing","order":2,"title":"Before the hearing","body":"<p>You&rsquo;ll be given a date for your hearing at least 14 days in advance. You&rsquo;ll have to prepare documents and witnesses.</p>\n\n<h2>Preliminary hearings</h2>\n\n<p>Sometimes there will be a preliminary hearing to decide how the case will be handled, eg if more evidence is needed.</p>\n\n<p>The tribunal will let you know:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>what will be discussed</li>\n  <li>if you&rsquo;ll have to give evidence or provide any extra information</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Arranging documents</h2>\n\n<p>You must give the employee 7 days&rsquo; notice of any documents that you&rsquo;ll be relying on as part of your case.</p>\n\n<p>You should bring 6 copies of each document, unless told otherwise.</p>\n\n<p>If the employee is part of a pension scheme, you must bring full details of the scheme to the tribunal.</p>\n\n<p>If the employee is asking to be reinstated, you must say whether this is possible, and if not, the reasons why.</p>\n\n<h2>Organising witnesses</h2>\n\n<p>You must only bring witnesses to the hearing if they can give evidence directly relevant to your case. </p>\n\n<p>If you call a witness and they don&rsquo;t want to attend, you can ask the tribunal to order them to come. You must apply in writing, in plenty of time, giving:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the name and address of the witness</li>\n  <li>what the witness will say and how it will help your case</li>\n  <li>why the witness has refused to come to the hearing</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You are usually responsible for paying the witness&rsquo;s costs.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/tribunals/employment/claims/guidance-booklets/ClaimForAttendingTribunal.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Party/witness expenses claim form for attending an employment tribunal' (PDF, 115KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Party/witness expenses claim form for attending an employment tribunal’ (PDF, 115KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Time off</h2>\n\n<p>The employee, if still employed by you, is entitled to full paid leave to attend the hearing.</p>\n\n<p>They can also ask a colleague to go with them. This colleague is also entitled to full paid leave.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/being-taken-to-employment-tribunal-by-employee/at-the-hearing","slug":"at-the-hearing","order":3,"title":"At the hearing","body":"<p>The full hearing will decide:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>whether the employee wins or loses their case</li>\n  <li>if they win, what &lsquo;remedy&rsquo; (eg compensation, getting their job back) they will get</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Bring all relevant documents and evidence to the hearing.</p>\n\n<h2>What happens at the hearing</h2>\n\n<p>You (or your representative) and the employee put your case to a panel or a judge, and answer questions.</p>\n\n<p>You can give evidence by reading a statement, if you want to.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You normally get the tribunal’s decision - or ‘judgment’ - on the day, but it may be sent in the post a few days after the hearing.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If you win the case</h2>\n\n<p>In most cases, you aren&rsquo;t awarded any compensation if the employee loses their case. In some cases, however, you may be awarded costs by the tribunal.</p>\n\n<h2>Expenses</h2>\n\n<p>You can&rsquo;t claim for expenses for going to the tribunal.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/being-taken-to-employment-tribunal-by-employee/lose-the-case","slug":"lose-the-case","order":4,"title":"If you lose the case","body":"<p>If you lose your case the tribunal can order you to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>pay compensation</li>\n  <li>give the employee their job back, if appropriate</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If it isn&rsquo;t appropriate or possible to reinstate the employee, you will pay compensation instead.</p>\n\n<h2>Paying compensation</h2>\n\n<p>Paying compensation is the most common outcome of a tribunal. There are usually limits to the amount of money a tribunal can award.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You have 42 days to pay the compensation.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t pay, you can be forced to do so - this includes being taken to court. You will also start to pay interest on the amount owed. </p>\n\n<p>The tribunal works out the amount using a formula based on the employee&rsquo;s age, salary and length of service.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>There is no compensation limit in cases of discrimination.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Paying back state benefits</h2>\n\n<p>Sometimes you will have to pay back any Jobseeker&rsquo;s Allowance or Income Support that the employee claimed while taking their case to the tribunal.</p>\n\n<p>This is to prevent the employee from getting paid twice.</p>\n\n<p>If this applies to you, the tribunal, then Jobcentre Plus will tell you what you need to do and how much to pay.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/being-taken-to-employment-tribunal-by-employee/if-you-disagree-with-a-tribunal-decision","slug":"if-you-disagree-with-a-tribunal-decision","order":5,"title":"If you disagree with a tribunal decision","body":"<p>You may be able to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>ask the tribunal to look at the case again</li>\n  <li>appeal to the Employment Appeal Tribunal</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Ask the tribunal to review the decision</h2>\n\n<p>Write to the tribunal within 14 days, saying why you want the decision to be reviewed. You must have a good reason, eg new evidence has turned up.</p>\n\n<p>Send your letter to the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/contacts/hmcts/tribunals/employment\" title=\"tribunal office\">tribunal office.</a></p>\n\n<h2>Appeal to the Employment Appeal Tribunal</h2>\n\n<p>You can also appeal to the Employment Appeal Tribunal if you think the employment tribunal made a legal mistake.</p>\n\n<p>Seek <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.lawsociety.org.uk/find-a-solicitor/\" title=\"legal advice\">legal advice</a> if you&rsquo;re unsure about this.</p>\n\n<p>Ask the employment tribunal to send you the reasons for the decision, if you don&rsquo;t alrea